coration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury </em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work. </strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects! </strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy </strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns! </strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats </em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals! </strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts </strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;3h 31m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-8-adjusting-the-fishtail-skirt-pattern/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-8-adjusting-the-fishtail-skirt-pattern/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-04T16:49:41+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-07T18:46:46+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 8. Adjusting the Fishtail Skirt Pattern."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 8. Adjusting the Fishtail Skirt Pattern."><meta itemprop="description" content="Let me remind you the previously calculated one sixths of all major half-circumferences which we will now use to calculate adjustments to the initial fishtail skirt pattern"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Theoretical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. theoretical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 8. Adjusting the Fishtail Skirt Pattern.</h1><h2>Adding a Train. Adjusting the Flare.</h2><p><strong>Let me remind you the previously calculated one sixths of all major half-circumferences which we will now use to calculate adjustments to the initial fishtail skirt pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>Waistline:</strong> Waist Width / 6 = 7.4cm / 2 = 3.7cm</p><p><strong>Stomach line: </strong>Stomach Width<br><img src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image002.png" alt="" height="20">/ 6 = 8.7cm / 2 = 4.4cm</p><p><strong>Hip line: </strong>Hip Width / 6 = 9.2cm / 2 = 4.6cm</p><p><strong>Now we can start adjusting the pattern. </strong></p><p><strong>The central back piece has already been modified.</strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image004.jpg" alt=""></p><p>I draw the stomach line and the hip line <strong>on the side back piece </strong>and mark 3.7cm left and right of the vertical midline along the waistline, 4.4cm along the stomach line, and 4.6cm along the hip line as follows from the calculations. These are one sixths of our client’s half-circumferences along these reference lines. I measure the distance between the found point on the hip line and the initial princess seam line and side seam line and shift them accordingly against the initial black lines. <strong>The adjusted back piece is ready and I only need to highlight the new outline. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image006.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Let us look at the initial front piece of the fishtail skirt pattern.</strong></p><p>Just like before, I draw the waistline, stomach line, and hip line <strong>on the central front piece </strong>cut with a fold line and mark 3.7cm, 4.4cm, and 4.6cm left and right of the fold line at the corresponding levels. I measure the distance between the found point on the hip line and the initial princess seam line to see how much smaller the Hip Circumference has become compared to the initial pattern. <strong>I sketch a new front princess seam line parallel to the initial line (blue dashed line). </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image008.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>At this stage, we need to account for the difference in the hip area of the front princess seam line. </strong>This area is marked by a red line on the initial pattern.</p><p><strong>Here is what I do. I shift the red part of the princess seam line inwards by the same value by which the Hip Circumference was reduced. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image010.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image012.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image014.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>As the result, the Stomach Circumference stays unchanged while the Hip Circumference becomes a little smaller compared to the client’s measurement. </strong>Let me remind you that we provided for a little looseness in all calculations related to the hip line. It is more than enough to make up for this slight reduction.</p><p><strong>It is another reason why it is always good to add some looseness allowance in calculations related to the hip line.</strong> Clients often ask you to make the skirt as tight as possible because they simply have no idea how uncomfortable it will be to wear it. Do not yield to the pressure – you can always narrow the skirt later.</p><p><strong>Let us move to the side front piece. </strong></p><p><strong>I adjust the entire princess seam line of the side front piece in correspondence with the same line of the central front piece. And I simply shift the side seam line by the calculated value. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image016.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I highlight the new lines with a marker. Now I have a set of customized patterns for cutting a classic fishtail skirt for a certain client. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image018.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>And now I would like to talk about certain situations when you need to apply some adjustments to the style or design of the standard skirt. </strong>As you know, there are lots of different styles of fishtail skirts. We will talk about the most popular ones.</p><p><strong>First of all, let me say a couple of words about adjusting the gore itself. </strong></p><p><strong>It is a common case when you need to insert an additional gore in the middle of the back of a fishtail skirt. </strong>You will need to determine its length yourself.</p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image020.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Useful tips: </strong>do not start the flare at an angle, but make a smooth rounded transition. Please note how the narrowest part of the gore on my pattern is found at the level where the flare begins. I would not recommend narrowing the gore additionally or moving this narrow area higher up. It will be hard to walk in the skirt if you do this.</p><p><strong>There are many cases when you need to change the width of the flare of the gore. </strong></p><p><strong>And there are certain rules and recommendations here as well. </strong></p><p><strong>If you want to adjust the width of the flare, make sure to do it symmetrically on all pieces. </strong></p><p><strong>Suppose you want to change the width of the gore sewn in the back princess seam of the skirt. </strong>In this case, you must apply relevant adjustments to the princess seam line of the side back piece and the princess seam line of the central back piece.</p><p><strong>I take the side back piece, </strong>draw a vertical line perpendicular to the hip line through point A (start point of the flare), and measure the existing width of the flare (B-C). It is 10.5cm on the standard pattern.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image022.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Suppose I want to make it 13cm instead of 10.5cm (B-D). </strong>I sketch a new line. The length of the gore from the start point A to the bottom is supposed to stay the same after I widen the flare. <strong>I set the initial gore length by securing a cord at point A and a pencil at point C. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image024.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I draw an arc stopping at the intersection with the new gore line (point D1). Now the length of the new gore (A-D1) fully coincides with the initial length (A-C). </strong></p><p>I adjust the bottom line of the gore to match the new flare width.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image026.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The same adjustments are applied to the corresponding side of the central front piece. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image028.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>There is an easier and more convenient way to do it.</strong></p><p>I apply adjustments to one gore and then use it as a template to re-draw the rest.</p><p><strong>Please remember: the skirt will only form beautiful folds if all its gores have the same amount of flare! </strong></p><p><strong>And now let us talk about adding a train to the skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>All trains are constructed the same way regardless of their length or shape.</strong></p><p><strong>I glue additional blank pages to the printed out central back piece and side back piece so I can show you how to draw a train. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image030.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>There is enough room for a small train </strong>of about 18cm on our half-scale pattern, which corresponds with 36cm in the actual size.</p><p><strong>Let me emphasize that all trains are constructed the same way regardless of their shape. </strong></p><p>The shape, however, can vary greatly: from a half-circle to a diamond or a triangle.</p><p><strong>In addition, there is one common rule: </strong>the flare of the train should be increased in proportion with its length to help it settle gracefully. The longer the train is, the more flared it should be.</p><p><strong>There is no fixed algorithm for constructing trains. </strong>I recommend you put your mock-up skirt on the dress-form and put it on the floor to decide on the length of the train.</p><p><strong>Since we are sewing a fitted silhouette dress </strong>which does not feature a petticoat, nothing adds to the volume of the skirt. The whole flare effect is created only by the gores.</p><p><strong>For this reason, you always start drawing a train from the side of the skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>The side seam length depends on the length of the train. </strong>The longer the train is, the more you have to prolong the side seam line to achieve a smooth transition from the front to the back.</p><p><strong>In order to determine the best train length and shape for your skirt, </strong>you can put a measuring tape along the bottom edge of the back half of the skirt and imagine roughly how much fabric you want to have lying on the floor, i.e. how long the train is supposed to be, and how the gores of the skirt will be arranged in this case.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image032.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And that is when the half-scale dress-form really comes in handy. </strong>You can estimate the length and width of each gore to create a beautiful train. As you understand, there are many factors which influence the final decision: the style and the length of the skirt, your client’s height, the level where the flare begins, as well as various properties of your fabric, such as softness and thickness, etc. In other words, you have to experiment each time. And that is why I insist upon sewing a mock-up when you start working on a new garment.</p><p><strong>Let us add a train to our fishtail skirt. </strong></p><p><strong>I prolong the central back seam line by 18cm, which corresponds with 36cm in the actual size. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image034.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>And now I need to find out how much longer the princess seam line should be made. </strong>Our skirt is flared evenly from all sides, which means the princess seam line of the side back piece will need to be prolonged by the same value.</p><p><strong>Relying on my personal experience, I recommend you add at least 2cm to the side seam line of the skirt when adding a small train. </strong>And remember: the more flare there is, the longer the side seam line should become.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I have prolonged the central back seam line by 18cm and the back side seam line by 2cm. </strong></p><p><strong>I can estimate how much to add to the princess seam line by calculating the arithmetic average between the value added to the central back seam line and the value added to the side seam line: </strong></p><p><strong>(18cm + 2cm) / 2 = 10cm</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>I can already sketch the shape of the bottom edge of the train at this stage. </strong></p><p>I suggest you first draw horizontal guidelines going from the bottom end points of the train, i.e. perpendicular to its sides, and then draw the bottom edge smoothly connecting them so the gores of the skirt can be joined at a straight angle.</p><p>I don’t like the resulting shape of the bottom edge with the back princess seam line prolonged by 10cm (dashed line). <strong>I prolong it by another 3.5cm so I can make the bottom edge of the train rounder. </strong>Of course, this is only a sketch for now.</p><p><strong>It always requires working with a mock-up to polish up the shape of the train! </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I add a train to the side back piece the same way, i.e. prolonging the princess seam line by 13.5cm and the side seam line by 2cm. </strong>I draw perpendicular lines from the bottom end points and draw the bottom edge of the train.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image042.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The preliminary draft is ready. </strong></p><p><strong>You may experiment a little at this stage: </strong>for example, keep <strong>increasing the flare of the skirt </strong>until you achieve the desired length of the bottom.</p><p><strong>It also looks gorgeous when the train starts from the middle of the skirt. </strong></p><p>It is a lot easier to achieve a beautiful train with a round bottom edge in that case.</p><p>The additional gore in the middle spreads out the skirt allowing you to make the bottom edge of the train rounder.</p><p><strong>After drawing the bottom edge of the train on the central back piece and on the side back piece, you can check how well they align. </strong></p><p><strong>I align the princess seam lines of the central back piece and the side back piece. </strong></p><p><strong>The resulting bottom edge of the train looks really bad! It is wavy! </strong></p><p><strong>The best way out is to prolong the princess seam lines additionally to achieve a smooth line (red line). </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image044.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>Do not forget about seam allowances.</strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>After drawing the train, you must apply adjustments to the front side piece: </strong></p><p><strong>- Firstly,</strong> add another 2.5cm to the flare and draw a smooth round bottom edge the same way you did on the back piece;</p><p><strong>- And, secondly,</strong> add 2cm to the side seam line (on the half-scale pattern).</p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%208.files/image048.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>We have prepared a set of patterns for sewing a fishtail skirt with a small train for our client. </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation Tables of All Parameters Required:</h3><p><strong><a href="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Tables/sun/index.htm" target="_blank">Trapeze-Sha